 future similar runs should prioritize truth-mapping, current state, and conflict detection over implementation optimism.\n\nKey steps:\n- Read the repo’s command surface from `package.json` and the benchmark scripts first.\n- Spawned read-only explorers for: entrypoint/flow mapping, prompt/instruction inventory, target workspace symmetry, autonomous runner mechanics, and proof gates/public evidence contract.\n- Verified that the repo has two layers: an older seed verified replay flow and a newer AST-Bench V1 scaffold.\n- Ran read-only validators (`benchmark:validate`, `benchmark:gates`, `proof:no-mock`) to confirm public guardrails without writing files.\n\nFailures and how to do differently:\n- The repo does not contain a DeepAgents/LangGraph runtime; treating it like one would be a category error. The autonomous behavior here comes from external agent CLIs launched by scripts, not an in-repo graph engine.\n- `benchmark:all` is presentation/scoring/gating, not agent execution. Future checks should not assume it refreshes autonomy evidence.\n- The generated AST-Bench acceptance tests are broken before the workflow can be tested: they reference `db`/`tables` globals that do not exist in test scope. The one successful AST run worked around this by injecting `globalThis.db = db` in production code, which means the agent was compensating for a harness bug rather than purely implementing business logic.\n\nReusable knowledge:\n- There is no root `AGENTS.md` / `CLAUDE.md` / Cursor instruction file in this repo; all `AGENTS.md` files are generated per target workspace or seed run.\n- The repo’s autonomous benchmark prompt is not a hidden system prompt; it is a CLI prompt string passed to `codex exec` plus the workspace `AGENTS.md` and README context.\n- AST-Bench V1 currently defines 25 tasks, 2 lanes, 3 agents, 3 repeats, and 450 required lane runs.\n- The current public state is legitimately `case-study`, not `public-v1`: `benchmark/results/summary.json` says 3 captured/passed lane runs and 447 missing.\n- The generated workspace layout is consistent: `package.json`, `AGENTS.md`, `README.md`, lane-shaped `data/`, `src/workflow.mjs`, `src/portal-view.mjs`, `src/render-proof.mjs`, `tests/acceptance.test.mjs`, and `tests-before.log`.\n- AST-Bench target workspaces are symmetric in structure but intentionally asymmetric in data modeling: MongoDB uses document-shaped collections; Postgres uses normalized relational tables.\n- Metrics are approximate: transcript tokens are estimated as `ceil(bytes / 4)`, and retry signals are crude regex counts over transcript/test text.\n\nReferences:\n- [1] `package.json`: `proof:*`, `instrumented:*`, and `benchmark:*` script families; especially the fact that `benchmark:all` does not run `benchmark:run`.\n- [2] `scripts/benchmark-lib.mjs`: current AST-Bench prompt template (`You are running AST-Bench, the Agent Schema Tax Benchmark.`) and the prompt rules.\n- [3] `scripts/benchmark-run.mjs`: the actual agent launch shapes for Codex/Claude/Cursor and the artifact capture flow.\n- [4] `scripts/benchmark-prepare.mjs`: generated target workspace layout and the malformed acceptance-test pattern.\n- [5] `scripts/benchmark-score.mjs`, `scripts/benchmark-gates.mjs`, `scripts/benchmark-build-public-bundle.mjs`: current scoring/gating/public-bundle behavior and caveats.\n- [6] `scripts/run-instrumented-codex.mjs` and `scripts/prepare-instrumented-run.mjs`: the older seed replay flow using `codex exec`.\n- [7] `benchmark/specs/ast-bench-v1.json`: 25 tasks, 2 lanes, 3 agents, 3 repeats, 450 lane runs, and the task catalog.\n- [8] `benchmark/results/summary.json`: `case-study`, 3 captured/passed lane runs, 447 missing.\n- [9] `instrumented-agent-runs/order-exception-codex-v1/mongo/prompt.md` and `.../postgres/prompt.md`: seed prompt text for the verified replay.\n- [10] `benchmark/runs/ast-bench-v1/renewal-risk-workspace/codex/repeat-1/mongo/workspace/tests/acceptance.test.mjs`: the broken AST-Bench generated test that references `db` at module scope.\n\n## Task 2: Compare system-prompt language and identify conflicts/drift\n\nOutcome: success\n\nPreference signals:\n- The user asked whether the agents “speak the same language” and have “the same idea” -> future similar analysis should explicitly compare wording across prompt layers, not just summarize each layer independently.\n- The user asked for the “full picture” -> future similar work should include stale naming, framing drift, and contradictory assumptions across seed vs benchmark layers.\n\nKey steps:\n- Compared root product language (`README.md`, `CONTEXT.md`, `PRODUCT.md`, `docs/PRD.md`) with generated prompt text.\n- Compared current AST-Bench prompts to older seed replay prompts.\n- Checked whether the benchmark actually has a repo-owned prompt or just CLI prompt text.\n- Used read-only evidence from the generated public bundle and verified replay artifacts to understand what the public-facing system says vs what the runtime actually uses.\n\nFailures and how to do differently:\n- The seed replay prompt is stale relative to the later AST-Bench framing. It still says “MongoDB’s Interactive Proof Lab,” while the current repo language puts AST-Bench first and uses Interactive Proof Lab as the rendering/theater layer.\n- The fairness contract in docs is stronger than the prompt text itself: docs talk about same prompt, agent, model/version, time budget, fixture version, failed attempts, and raw evidence links, but the prompt string only covers task/acceptance/native-model/no-test-edit/no-simulation rules.\n- Captured Codex runs are not hermetic because the agent read `~/.codex/memories/MEMORY.md`; future fair comparisons should treat global agent memory/config as part of the environment contract.\n- Root demo metrics are inconsistent across docs (`README.md` vs `docs/seller-demo-script.md`), so public-facing numbers need careful source selection.\n\nReusable knowledge:\n- Current AST-Bench prompt template: “You are running AST-Bench, the Agent Schema Tax Benchmark,” followed by task title, business request, acceptance criteria, native model rule, `npm test`, and “Do not hand-wave or simulate evidence.”\n- Older seed prompt template: “You are running an Instrumented Agent Run for MongoDB’s Interactive Proof Lab,” followed by the Customer 360 Escalation task for `HX-20491` / `acct-nova`, exact portal outcomes, and the “do not change tests/data” rule.\n- Generated `AGENTS.md` files are terse and task-specific; they are not the authoritative system prompt, but they do constrain implementation in each workspace.\n- The public bundle and no-mock gate encode stronger public-proof language than the seed prompts do.\n\nReferences:\n- [1] `scripts/benchmark-lib.mjs:172-192` current AST-Bench prompt template.\n- [2] `instrumented-agent-runs/order-exception-codex-v1/mongo/prompt.md:1-25` older seed prompt template.\n- [3] `benchmark/targets/strategic-account-rescue/mongo/workspace/AGENTS.md:1-8` and `.../postgres/...`: current generated target rules.\n- [4] `instrumented-agent-runs/order-exception-codex-v1/mongo/workspace/AGENTS.md:1-7`: seed workspace rules.\n- [5] `README.md`, `CONTEXT.md`, `PRODUCT.md`, `docs/PRD.md`: root language about AST-Bench, case-study status, and no guaranteed savings.\n- [6] `docs/future-agent-lanes.md`: current sequencing/claim rule for future agents.\n- [7] `benchmark/runs/ast-bench-v1/renewal-risk-workspace/codex/repeat-1/mongo/raw-transcript/codex.jsonl`: evidence that Codex read global memory during a run.\n\n## Task 3: Distinguish proof correctness from autonomy correctness\n\nOutcome: success\n\nPreference signals:\n- The user asked to understand what autonomous behavior “might be broken” -> future similar work should separate proof-gate correctness from actual agent autonomy.\n- The user framed this as a regression-stop moment -> future similar work should highlight anything that can pass while hiding broken autonomy.\n\nKey steps:\n- Ran read-only validators: `npm run benchmark:validate`, `npm run benchmark:gates`, and `npm run proof:no-mock`; all passed.\n- Inspected the verified replay chain, the evidence-manifest integrity checks, and the public bundle assembly.\n- Checked the generated local DB proof and the current benchmark summary.\n- Compared evidence-building scripts with actual execution scripts to see what is validated vs what is just packaged.\n\nFailures and how to do differently:\n- `check-no-mock-data` is primarily a public-surface/copy guard, not a deep autonomy validator.\n- The proof gates trust existing artifacts; they do not re-run Codex. That means verified evidence can be maintained even if the live execution path regresses later.\n- `benchmark-gates` does not assert agent exit codes, command counts, non-empty transcripts, or recomputed source hashes; it mainly checks existing manifests/artifacts and no test/data edits.\n- The current benchmark can still be thin and unbalanced while passing public gates; the current result is only 3/450.\n\nReusable knowledge:\n- Verified replay promotion requires passed instrumented summary, captured design review, passed MongoDB/Postgres local DB proofs, matching fixture versions, and per-lane raw transcript/diff/tests/acceptance/screenshot artifacts.\n- `check-proof-gates` verifies evidence-manifest integrity with SHA-256 equality.\n- `build-public-evidence-bundle` is packaging/presentation, not proof by itself.\n- `proof:verified` is the stronger seed-proof path; `proof:gates` defaults to the candidate replay, not the verified replay.\n- The old candidate replay remains present and explicitly marked as candidate/local-runner evidence, not verified live-agent proof.\n\nReferences:\n- [1] `scripts/check-proof-gates.mjs:15-28`, `:52-72`.\n- [2] `scripts/promote-verified-replay.mjs:24-35`, `:51-60`, `:135-137`.\n- [3] `scripts/build-public-evidence-bundle.mjs:35-90`, `:601-604`.\n- [4] `scripts/check-no-mock-data.mjs:20-39`, `:72-88`, `:109-128`.\n- [5] `b